The Chief Justice of Nigeria (CJN), Justice Ibrahim Tanko Muhammad, has called on state governors to respect the independence of the judiciary especially its financial autonomy. Justice Tanko Muhammad made the plea at the commissioning ceremony of Justice Umaru Abdullahi healthcare facility for the judiciary officers yesterday in Katsina State. According to him, the healthcare facilities which is exclusively made for judicial officers is highly commendable and timely, considering the health need and challenges facing the sector as a result of their long hours of work done manually. The CJN, who was represented by Supreme Court judge, Wani Abba Aji, thanked Governor Aminu Masari for initiating the first exclusive health facility for any state judiciary, urging other governors to emulate him. He reiterated that “ I have had course severally to appeal to Chief Executives to always respect provision of the independent and financial autonomy of the judiciary branch. “The three branches of government as provided under the Constitution are partners in ensuring good governance and sustenance of democracy, unfortunately the judiciary in most cases is unable to perform optimally as a result of the financial dependence on the Executive branch, a situation where many had to go begging which negate the principle of separation of power and true democracy.” He added that Katsina State seems to be different in terms of judiciary autonomy, saying that he has been informed by the state chief Judge, that for the past three years the state judiciary arm has been receiving 100 per cent budget performance which is not obtainable in some states. Also addressing the gathering, Governor Aminu Bello Masari, thanked the Chief Justice of Nigeria for commissioning the edifice, and expressed his administration’s support for the judiciary arm. He maintained that aside giving approval for the construction of the project, the state government has spent huge amount of money in upgrading and equipping judiciary facilities in the state.